005/**
006 * Arbitrary-dimensional continuous noise that maintains most of the same style even as the dimensionality gets fairly
007 * high. If you know what dimension of noise you need, and it's covered by {@link FoamNoise} (meaning it's 2D, 3D, 4D,
008 * or 6D noise), then using FoamNoise will give you a significantly faster version of approximately the same algorithm.
009 * If your noise has an unknown dimension count, this won't really work either, since PhantomNoise needs to do some
010 * preparation and allocation for a specific dimension in its constructor. But, if you know what the range of dimensions
011 * is, and the lowest is at least 2D, you can make one PhantomNoise per dimension easily enough.
012 * <br>
013 * The algorithm this uses is surprisingly simple. To produce N-D noise, it makes N+1 calls to N-D value noise, with
014 * each call using a different rotation of the same size of grid. It "domain warps" value noise calls after the first,
015 * adding the previous value noise result to one coordinate of the next value noise call. To get a PhantomNoise result,
016 * it averages all the value noise calls and curves the output range so it doesn't get more biased toward 0 with higher
017 * dimensions (which would happen with a pure average of a rising number of variables). The curving here uses the
018 * {@link MathExtras#barronSpline(double, double, double)} method for adjustable bias/gain; it looks
019 * <a href="https://i.imgur.com/fchQOuP.png">like this for 2D</a>,
020 * <a href="https://i.imgur.com/vpc2XGq.png">like this for 3D</a>, and
021 * <a href="https://i.imgur.com/fNWJOEp.png">like this for 4D</a>.
022 * There's some preparation this does in the constructor, which eliminates the need for allocations during noise
023 * generation. For N-D PhantomNoise, this makes N+1 double arrays, one for each rotation for a value noise call, and
024 * each rotation array has N items. The rotations match the vertices of an N-simplex, so a triangle in 2D, a tetrahedron
025 * in 3D, etc. It also stores two working-room arrays, each with N+1 double items, two frequently-edited int arrays of
026 * the floors of doubles it's using, and of modified versions of those floors to be hashed (each with N+1 items), and
027 * interestingly, a {@link CrossHash.Curlup} hash functor, seeded in the PhantomNoise constructor.
028 * <br>
029 * At higher dimensions, Simplex noise (what {@link SeededNoise} produces) starts to change how it looks compared to
030 * lower dimensions. PhantomNoise, on the other hand, maintains a fairly consistent blob-like organic look, such as
031 * <a href="https://i.imgur.com/wxomHAc.png">this 6D PhantomNoise sample</a>. Red and purple mark the highest and lowest
032 * possible values, respectively, and while they appear plenty in PhantomNoise, they are absent in
033 * <a href="https://i.imgur.com/2t7hRtk.png">this 6D SeededNoise sample</a>. There may be differences in how the inputs
034 * are handled between the two samples, but 6D Simplex generally suffers from "the curse of dimensionality" more-so than
035 * PhantomNoise (or Perlin noise like {@link ClassicNoise}, somewhat surprisingly), with the "curse" affecting the
036 * density of information in higher-dimensional space.
037 * <br>
038 * This is marked Beta because it's still pretty slow at higher dimensions, and if some optimization becomes available
039 * here, I'll take it and the output will change from this version.
040 */
041@Beta
042public class PhantomNoise {
043    private final CrossHash.Curlup yolk;
044    public final int dim;
045    private final double inverse, sharpness;
046    private final double[] working, points;
047    private final double[][] vertices;
048    private final int[] floors, hashFloors;
049    public PhantomNoise() {
050        this(0xFEEDBEEF1337CAFEL, 3);
051    }
052
053    public PhantomNoise(long seed, int dimension) {
054        this(seed, dimension, 0.825 * Math.max(2, dimension));
055    }
056    public PhantomNoise(long seed, int dimension, double sharpness) {
057        dim = Math.max(2, dimension);
058        this.sharpness = sharpness;
059        working = new double[dim+1];
060        points = new double[dim+1];
061        vertices = new double[dim+1][dim];
062        double id = -1.0 / dim;
063        vertices[0][0] = 1.0;
064        for (int v = 1; v <= dim; v++) {
065            vertices[v][0] = id;
066        }
067        for (int d = 1; d < dim; d++) {
068            double t = 0.0;
069            for (int i = 0; i < d; i++) {
070                t += vertices[d][i] * vertices[d][i];
071            }
072            vertices[d][d] = Math.sqrt(1.0 - t);
073            t = (id - t) / vertices[d][d];
074            for (int v = d + 1; v <= dim; v++) {
075                vertices[v][d] = t;
076            }
077        }
078        for (int v = 0; v <= dim; v++) {
079            final double theta = NumberTools.atan2(vertices[v][1], vertices[v][0]) + 0.6180339887498949,
080                    dist = Math.sqrt(vertices[v][1] * vertices[v][1] + vertices[v][0] * vertices[v][0]);
081            vertices[v][0] = NumberTools.cos(theta) * dist;
082            vertices[v][1] = NumberTools.sin(theta) * dist;
083        }
084        floors = new int[dim+1];
085        hashFloors = new int[dim+1];
086        yolk = new CrossHash.Curlup(seed);
087        inverse = 1.0 / (dim + 1.0);
088//        printDebugInfo();
089    }
090
091    protected double valueNoise()
092    {
093        hashFloors[dim] = NumberTools.doubleToMixedIntBits(working[dim]);
094        for (int i = 0; i < dim; i++) {
095            floors[i] = working[i] >= 0.0 ? (int)working[i] : (int)working[i] - 1;
096            working[i] -= floors[i];
097            working[i] *= working[i] * (3.0 - 2.0 * working[i]);
098        }
099        double sum = 0.0, temp;
100        final int limit = 1 << dim;
101        int bit;
102        for (int i = 0; i < limit; i++) {
103            temp = 1.0;
104            for (int j = 0; j < dim; j++) {
105                bit = (i >>> j & 1);
106                temp *= bit + (1|-bit) * working[j];
107                hashFloors[j] = floors[j] - bit;
108            }
109            sum += temp * yolk.hash(hashFloors);
110        }
111        return (sum * 0x1p-32 + 0.5);
112    }
113
114    protected double valueNoise2D()
115    {
116        hashFloors[2] = NumberTools.doubleToMixedIntBits(working[2]);
117        for (int i = 0; i < 2; i++) {
118            floors[i] = working[i] >= 0.0 ? (int)working[i] : (int)working[i] - 1;
119            working[i] -= floors[i];
120            working[i] *= working[i] * (3.0 - 2.0 * working[i]);
121        }
122        double sum = 0.0, temp;
123        int bit;
124        for (int i = 0; i < 4; i++) {
125            temp = 1.0;
126            
127            bit = i;
128            temp *= bit + (1|-bit) * working[0];
129            hashFloors[0] = floors[0] - bit;
130            
131            bit = i >>> 1;
132            temp *= bit + (1|-bit) * working[1];
133            hashFloors[1] = floors[1] - bit;
134            
135            sum += temp * yolk.hash(hashFloors);
136        }
137        return (sum * 0x1p-32 + 0.5);
138    }
139    
140    public double getNoise(double... args) {
141        for (int v = 0; v <= dim; v++) {
142            points[v] = 0.0;
143            for (int d = 0; d < dim; d++) {
144                points[v] += args[d] * vertices[v][d];
145            }
146        }
147        working[dim] = 0.6180339887498949; // inverse golden ratio; irrational, so its bit representation nears random
148        double result = 0.0, warp = 0.0;
149        for (int i = 0; i <= dim; i++) {
150            for (int j = 0, d = 0; j < dim; j++, d++) {
151                if(d == i) d++;
152                working[j] = points[d];
153            }
154            working[0] += warp;
155            warp = valueNoise();
156            result += warp;
157            working[dim] += -0.423310825130748; // e - pi
158        }
159        result *= inverse;
160        final double diff = 0.5 - result;
161        final int sign = NumberTools.doubleToHighIntBits(diff) >> 31, one = sign | 1;
162        return (((result + sign)) / (Double.MIN_VALUE - sign + (result + sharpness * diff) * one) - sign - sign) - 1.0;
163//        return (result <= 0.5)
164//                ? Math.pow(result * 2, dim) - 1.0
165//                : Math.pow((result - 1) * 2, dim) * (((dim & 1) << 1) - 1) + 1.0;
166        
167//        for (int i = 1; i < dim; i++) {
168//            result *= result * (3.0 - 2.0 * result);
169//        }
170//        return  (result * result * (6.0 - 4.0 * result) - 1.0);
171    }

173    public double getNoise2D(double x, double y) {
174        points[0] = -0.4161468365471422 * x + 0.9092974268256818 * y;
175        points[1] = -0.5794012529532914 * x + -0.8150424455671962 * y;
176        points[2] = 0.9955480895004332 * x + -0.09425498125848553 * y;
177        working[2] = 0.6180339887498949;
178        double result = 0.0, warp = 0.0;
179        for (int i = 0; i <= 2; i++) {
180            for (int j = 0, d = 0; j < 2; j++, d++) {
181                if(d == i) d++;
182                working[j] = points[d] + warp;
183            }
184            warp = valueNoise2D();
185            result += warp;
186            working[2] += -0.423310825130748;
187        }
188        result *= inverse;
189        final double diff = 0.5 - result;
190        final int sign = NumberTools.doubleToHighIntBits(diff) >> 31, one = sign | 1;
191        return (((result + sign)) / (Double.MIN_VALUE - sign + (result + sharpness * diff) * one) - sign - sign) - 1.0;
192        
193//        return MathExtras.barronSpline(result, dim * (2.0 + 0.5 * dim), 0.5) * 2.0 - 1.0;
194        
195//        return (result <= 0.5)
196//                ? (result * result * 4) - 1.0
197//                : ((result - 1) * (result - 1) * -4) + 1.0;
198
199//        result *= result * (3.0 - 2.0 * result);
200//        return  (result * result * (6.0 - 4.0 * result) - 1.0);
201    }

203    void printDebugInfo(){         
204        System.out.println("PhantomNoise with Dimension " + dim + ":");
205        final String dimNames = "xyzwuvabcdefghijklmnopqrst";
206        for (int v = 0; v <= dim; v++) {
207            System.out.print("points[" + v + "] = ");
208            for (int i = 0; i < dim; i++) {
209                if(vertices[v][i] != 0.0) 
210                {
211                    if(i > 0)
212                        System.out.print(" + ");
213                    if(vertices[v][i] == 1.0)
214                        System.out.print(dimNames.charAt(i % dimNames.length()));
215                    else 
216                        System.out.print(dimNames.charAt(i % dimNames.length()) + " * " + vertices[v][i]);
217                }
218            }
219            System.out.println(';');
220        }
221    }
